title: (523684) 2014 CQ23
text:
, provisional designation , is a <a href="trans-Neptunian%20object">trans-Neptunian object</a> and <a href="cubewano">cubewano</a> from the <a href="Kuiper%20belt">Kuiper belt</a>, located in the outermost region of the <a href="Solar%20System">Solar System</a>. It was discovered on 13 March 2011, by astronomers with the <a href="Pan-STARRS">Pan-STARRS</a> survey at <a href="Haleakala%20Observatory">Haleakala Observatory</a>, Hawaii, United States. The <a href="classical%20Kuiper%20belt%20object">classical Kuiper belt object</a> belongs to the <a href="Hot%20classical">hot population</a> and is a <a href="List%20of%20possible%20dwarf%20planets">dwarf planet candidate</a>, as it measures approximately in diameter.
Orbit and classification.
 is a <a href="cubewano">cubewano</a>, a classical, low-eccentricity object in the <a href="Kuiper%20belt">Kuiper belt</a>, located in between the two resonant <a href="plutino">plutino</a> and <a href="twotino">twotino</a> populations, and belongs to the "stirred" <a href="Hot%20classical">hot population</a> rather than to the <a href="Cold%20classical">cold population</a> with low inclinations.
It orbits the Sun at a distance of 38.7–53.7 <a href="Astronomical%20unit">AU</a> once every 313 years and 8 months (114,565 days; <a href="semi-major%20axis">semi-major axis</a> of 46.16 AU). Its orbit has an <a href="orbital%20eccentricity">eccentricity</a> of 0.16 and an <a href="orbital%20inclination">inclination</a> of 9<a href="Degree%20%28angle%29">°</a> with respect to the <a href="ecliptic">ecliptic</a>.
Numbering and naming.
This <a href="minor%20planet">minor planet</a> was <a href="Minor%20planet%20designation">numbered</a> by the <a href="Minor%20Planet%20Center">Minor Planet Center</a> on 25 September 2018 and received the number in the <a href="LOMP">minor planet catalog</a> (). As of 2018, it has not been <a href="List%20of%20named%20minor%20planets%20%28numerical%29">named</a>.
Physical characteristics.
According to the American astronomer <a href="Michael%20E.%20Brown">Michael Brown</a>, measures 343 kilometers in diameter based on an assumed <a href="astronomical%20albedo">albedo</a> of 0.08. On his website, Michael Brown lists this object as a <a href="List%20of%20possible%20dwarf%20planets">"possible" dwarf planet</a> (200–400 km), which is the category with the lowest certainty in his <a href="List%20of%20possible%20dwarf%20planets%23Brown%27s%20assessment">5-class taxonomic system</a>. Similarly, Johnston's archive estimates a diameter 321 kilometers using an albedo of 0.09. As of 2018, neither a <a href="Distant%20object%20spectral%20type">spectral type</a> or the <a href="Distant%20object%20color%20indices">color indices</a> have been determined, nor a rotational <a href="lightcurve">lightcurve</a> has been obtained from <a href="Astronomical%20spectroscopy%23Planets%2C%20asteroids%2C%20and%20comets">spectroscopic</a> and <a href="Photometry%20%28astronomy%29">photometric</a> observations. The body's color, <a href="rotation%20period">rotation period</a>, <a href="Poles%20of%20astronomical%20bodies">pole</a> and shape remain unknown.
